Let \(U\sim\chi^2_{
u_1}\) and \(V\sim\chi^2_{
u_2}\) be independent. State the random variable that has an \(F_{
u_1,
u_2}\) distribution and identify which degrees of freedom belong to the numerator and denominator.

The F statistic is \[F= rac{U/
u_1}{V/
u_2}\sim F_{
u_1,
u_2}.\] The first degree of freedom \(
u_1\) belongs to the numerator chi-squared variable. The second degree of freedom \(
u_2\) belongs to the denominator chi-squared variable. The order matters because the F distribution is not symmetric.

Every variance-ratio problem is an F-distribution problem only after you verify which sample variance is in the numerator.
